    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>Brix and Refractometers in Brewing</h2>
      <p>
        Brix is a percentage-by-weight scale of dissolved sucrose. A refractometer is a small optical instrument that measures Brix by shining a light through a few drops of sample and detecting the angle at which the light bends. The bigger the bend, the more dissolved solids in the liquid. Refractometers are loved by brewers because they need only two or three drops, work in seconds, and survive years of abuse on the brew deck. The trade-off is that the conversion to specific gravity is straightforward only for unfermented wort; once alcohol enters the picture, you need a correction equation.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>The Wort Correction Factor</h2>
      <p>
        Refractometers are calibrated for sucrose solutions, but wort is not pure sucrose. Wort contains maltose, maltotriose, dextrins, proteins, and various non-sugar dissolved solids that bend light slightly differently than pure sucrose. The correction factor that bridges the gap is called the wort correction factor or WCF, and a value of 1.04 means your refractometer reads 4 percent higher in Brix than the actual extract content of the wort. To find your specific WCF, take simultaneous readings on the same wort sample with a refractometer and a calibrated hydrometer, then divide the refractometer Brix by the Brix derived from the hydrometer SG. Most all-grain brewers land between 1.02 and 1.06.
      </p>

      <h2>Post-Fermentation Conversion Using Terrill's Cubic</h2>
      <p>
        Once fermentation produces alcohol, a simple Brix to SG conversion is no longer accurate because alcohol bends light differently than sugar. Sean Terrill developed a cubic regression in 2011 that uses both the OG Brix and the FG Brix, applies the WCF to both, and returns a corrected final gravity that closely matches a hydrometer reading. The equation is mathematically ugly but reliably accurate to within 0.001 to 0.002 SG when compared with measured values. This calculator runs the Terrill cubic automatically when you fill in both OG and FG Brix, so you can take both measurements with a refractometer and skip the hydrometer entirely for routine brewing.
      </p>

      <h2>Refractometer vs Hydrometer Trade-Offs</h2>
      <p>
        For original gravity, both instruments are equally accurate when used correctly. For final gravity, a hydrometer wins by a small margin because it measures density directly without needing an alcohol correction. The hydrometer downside is sample size: a trial jar needs 100 to 200 mL of beer, which has to be discarded or sanitized to return. A refractometer needs three drops, which means you can take measurements throughout fermentation without losing meaningful volume from the carboy. Most brewers eventually use both: a refractometer for daily fermentation tracking and a hydrometer for the final, official, archive-worthy reading.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is Brix?</h3>
      <p>
        Brix is the percentage of dissolved sucrose by weight. Refractometers measure it optically. One degree Brix equals one gram of sucrose per 100 grams of solution.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the wort correction factor?</h3>
      <p>
        The WCF corrects for the difference in refractive index between sucrose and actual wort. A WCF of 1.04 means the refractometer reads 4 percent higher in Brix than the true wort extract content.
      </p>

      <h3>Why doesn't a plain Brix to SG formula work after fermentation?</h3>
      <p>
        Alcohol bends light differently than sugar and skews the refractive index reading. The Sean Terrill cubic equation corrects for the alcohol contribution and returns a true SG.
      </p>

      <h3>How accurate is this calculator?</h3>
      <p>
        Within 0.001 to 0.002 specific gravity points compared to a hydrometer reading, assuming your WCF is correct.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I find my refractometer's WCF?</h3>
      <p>
        Take simultaneous refractometer and hydrometer readings on the same unfermented wort sample, then divide the refractometer Brix by the SG-derived Brix. Average the result over several batches for the best accuracy.
      </p>

